I now have everything I need. The knowledge graph has confirmed the complete picture across AP-064, EAP-077, and EAP-080 with their full incident history. Let me deliver the full diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

The display-scale title input in the case-study editor is clipping the top of IBM Plex Serif cap-height glyphs. You correctly identified that bumping `padding-top` does nothing — it just shifts the whole box down, the glyphs still sit flush against the top of their line box. This is the canonical symptom of **AP-064 / EAP-077**.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-064** + **EAP-077**: Native `<input>` text rendering clips display-scale serif fonts at the top.

The mechanism is a three-layer problem — not a padding problem:

### Layer 1 — The `<input>` line-height trap

Native `<input>` elements use UA-supplied `line-height: normal`, which resolves to approximately `1.2 × font-size`. For IBM Plex Serif at the `heading-case-study-intro` scale (~36–60px fluid), "normal" produces a line box with virtually zero internal leading. The font's **ascenders and cap-height** of a display-weight serif extend above the nominal em-square boundary and protrude into the line box's *half-leading* (the space above the text baseline). When the line box has no meaningful half-leading, those protruding features are **geometrically outside the content area** before any rendering clip is even applied.

### Layer 2 — The browser rendering clip for `<input>`

Browsers apply a painting clip to `<input>` text at the content-box boundary (inset by padding). This is a **native rendering clip**, not CSS `overflow: hidden`. It is applied by the browser's form-control renderer before CSS cascade, and **cannot be overridden with CSS alone** — not with `overflow: visible`, not with `padding-top`, not with `clip: auto`. The only CSS knob that actually moves the rendering clip boundary is `line-height`, because `line-height` sets the height of the line box itself, which is what the native renderer clips to.

> This is what EAP-077 documents: "Assuming CSS Can Fix `<input>` Native Text Clipping for Oversized Serif Fonts" — adding padding-top is the specific trap, because padding only moves the box, it does not change where the renderer clips the text.

### Layer 3 — IBM Plex Serif's tall ascender metrics

IBM Plex Serif has unusually generous ascender metrics — its cap-height sits very near the em-square top, with almost no internal font padding above capital letters. At body scale this is invisible. At display scale (36–60px), even a `line-height: 1.25` (the `heading-case-study-intro` mixin value) leaves insufficient half-leading above capitals. The specific clipping point is the serif's **bracket detail at cap-height** — the small horizontal stroke at the top of a capital letter, which is the first thing to disappear when the line box is too tight.

---

## Fix

The fix is **not** `padding-top`. It is `line-height` on the `<input>` element itself, combined with replacing the `<input>` with a styled `<textarea>` or `contenteditable` if full rendering control is needed. Specifically for this case-study editor display title:

### Option A — Preferred: Replace `<input>` with `<textarea rows="1">` (AP-064 canonical fix)

A `<textarea>` renders text through the standard CSS painting pipeline, not the native form-control renderer. This means `overflow: hidden`, `line-height`, and padding all work correctly.

**File:** `src/app/(frontend)/work/[slug]/inline-edit.module.scss` (or wherever the display title input is styled)

```scss
// BEFORE — native <input> with clipping
.displayTitleInput {
  @include heading-case-study-intro;
  // padding-top: Npx; ← this never works, remove it
  width: 100%;
  border: none;
  background: transparent;
  resize: none;
}

// AFTER — textarea with glyph-safe line height
.displayTitleInput {
  @include heading-case-study-intro;
  // heading-case-study-intro gives line-height: 1.25 (snug)
  // At 60px that's 75px line box — still clips IBM Plex Serif bracket serifs.
  // Override to 1.35 minimum for display-scale serif glyphs:
  line-height: 1.35;
  width: 100%;
  border: none;
  background: transparent;
  resize: none;
  overflow: hidden;           // safe on <textarea> unlike <input>
  field-sizing: content;      // CSS WD: auto-grow to content; fallback below
  // Fallback height for browsers without field-sizing:
  min-height: calc(1.35em + var(--spacing-top-glyph-safe, 4px));
  padding-top: 2px;           // now this actually works — not clipped by native renderer
}
```

**File:** wherever the editor JSX renders the title — replace:
```tsx
// BEFORE
<input
  className={styles.displayTitleInput}
  value={title}
  onChange={e => setTitle(e.target.value)}
/>

// AFTER
<textarea
  ref={titleRef}
  className={styles.displayTitleInput}
  value={title}
  onChange={e => setTitle(e.target.value)}
  rows={1}
  onInput={e => {
    // Auto-height for browsers without field-sizing
    const el = e.currentTarget;
    el.style.height = 'auto';
    el.style.height = `${el.scrollHeight}px`;
  }}
/>
```

### Option B — Minimal: Keep `<input>`, fix line-height

If swapping to `<textarea>` is out of scope right now, the minimum viable fix is to set `line-height` large enough that the native renderer's line box contains the full ascender:

```scss
.displayTitleInput {
  @include heading-case-study-intro;
  line-height: 1.4;   // ← was implicitly 1.25 from the mixin; 1.4 clears IBM Plex Serif cap-height
  // DO NOT add padding-top to fix clipping — it won't work on <input>
}
```

This will make the input taller than the rendered headline (since an `<input>` can't shrink its height below `line-height × font-size`), which is why Option A is preferred.

### The `overflow: hidden` secondary risk (EAP-080)

If there is any wrapper element around the title input with `overflow: hidden` — e.g. a `.sectionToolbar`, `.blockWrapper`, or an animation container — that will cause a secondary clip on the glyph even after the `line-height` fix. EAP-080 mandates a "glyph padding" audit whenever `overflow: hidden` meets display-scale serif:

```scss
// Any ancestor of the title input that has overflow: hidden must have glyph padding:
.titleContainer {
  overflow: hidden;
  padding-top: 0.1em;  // glyph-safe overflow buffer for IBM Plex Serif ascenders
  // This works on a <div> container — overflow: hidden on a div uses the CSS painting pipeline,
  // not the native input renderer, so padding-top here correctly expands the clip boundary.
}
```

---

## Why `padding-top` on `<input>` fails (structural explanation for display-scale fonts)

Here is the structural difference between a body-scale input and a display-scale serif input:

| Factor | Body scale (16–18px) | Display scale (36–60px) |
|---|---|---|
| `line-height: normal` result | ~19–22px | ~43–72px |
| IBM Plex Serif cap-height above baseline | ~11px | ~42px |
| Glyph ascenders (brackets, serifs) above nominal cap | ~1–2px | ~4–8px |
| Percentage of line box consumed by ascenders | <10% — fits in UA padding | >15% — native clip fires |
| Effect of `padding-top` | Moves box down, glyphs move with it ✓ | Moves box down, glyphs move with it, but clip boundary = line box top = still hits cap ✗ |

The fundamental structural difference: **`padding-top` shifts where the line box is painted, but the native rendering clip is relative to the line box, not the padding edge.** So adding padding just translates the problem without solving it. The clip boundary moves with the line box, which means cap-height glyphs that sit at the top of their line box remain clipped regardless of how much padding you add.

`line-height` is the correct lever because it directly controls the height of the line box itself. A taller line box means the cap-height sits proportionally lower within it, so the rendering clip at the top of the line box no longer intersects the glyphs.

---

## Principle

**AP-064** (design) + **EAP-077** (engineering): IBM Plex Serif at display scale cannot use native `<input>` for glyph-safe rendering. The fix is `line-height ≥ 1.35` and, for full control, replacing `<input>` with `<textarea rows="1">`. `padding-top` is a documented false fix for this specific pattern — it is cosmetically plausible but mechanically inert at the native renderer level.

**EAP-080** companion check: audit all ancestors of the title field for `overflow: hidden` and add `padding-top: 0.1em` glyph buffer where needed. This is a separate clip mechanism from the `<input>` native clip, and it will survive the `line-height` fix independently.
